
To monitor CPU, memory, disk usage, network activity, and running processes.
1.ps aux vs top
==>ps aux Command
Type: Snapshot command
Purpose: Shows the current status of processes at one moment in time.
What it does:
Displays all running processes
Shows:
CPU usage (%CPU)
Memory usage (%MEM)

===>top Command
top command give live process update
Type: Real-time monitoring tool
Purpose: Continuously monitors system performance.
What it does:
Shows real-time CPU usage
Shows memory usage
Updates every few seconds
Shows load average
Allows interaction (kill process, change priority)


===>How many cpu  in virtual meachine as we can check by using command 
nproc

cpu--> top
memory-->free -h
disk--> df -h


====================================================================
Networking Commands
ping google.com – Checks connectivity to a remote server.
ifconfig – Displays network interfaces (deprecated, use ip).
ip a – Shows IP addresses of network interfaces.
netstat -tulnp – Displays open network connections.
curl https://example.com – Fetches a webpage's content.
wget https://example.com/file.zip – Downloads a file from the internet.






